    "Q3. What are the different types of data and how do they differ from each other? Provide an example of\n",
    "    each type of data.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    ANS--There are two types of data--\n",
    "    1.QUANTITATIVE --Quantitative data can be measured and is not just observable.                                        \n",
    "                   The measurement of data is numerically recorded and represented.\n",
    "      There are two types --1)Discrete--Discrete data refers to the data values which can only attain\n",
    "                                        certain specific values\n",
    "                                          Discrete data can’t attain a range of values\n",
    "                                           example--The number of students in a class,\n",
    "                                                    The number of chips in a bag,\n",
    "                                                    The number of stars in the sky\n",
    "                             2)Continuous--Continuous Data can contain values between a certain range that \n",
    "                                            is within the highest and lowest values.\\n\",\n",
    "                                        example--Height and weight of a student,\n",
    "                                                   Daily temperature recordings of a place\n",
    "                                                    Wind speed measurement.\n",
    "    2.QUALITATIVE--Qualitative data is used to represent some characteristics or attributes of the data.\n",
    "                    The facts and figures depicted by the qualitative data cannot be computed.\n",
    "       There are two types---1)Norminal--Nominal data is a sub-category belonging to one of the types of qualitative information\n",
    "                                  example--Gender (Women, Men)\n",
    "                                           Eye color (Blue, Green, Brown)\n",
    "                                          Hair color (Blonde, Brown, Brunette, Red, etc.)\n",
    "                                           Marital status (Married, Single)\n",
    "                                           Religion (Muslim, Hindu, Christian)\n",
    "                           2)Ordinal---Ordinal data/variable is the specific type of data that follows a natural order\n",
    "                                   example---Feedback is recorded in the form of ratings from 1-10.\n",
    "                                                 Education level: elementary school, high school, college.\n",
    "                                              Economic status: low, medium, and high.\n",
    "                                           Letter grades: A, B, C, and etc.\n",
    "                                              Customer level of satisfaction: very satisfied, satisfied, neutral, dissatisfied, very dissatisfied.\n",
    "   \n",
    "  "
   ]
